<div id="review_147962317" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/147962317" />
    <a title="Caren" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2610234-caren"><img alt="Caren" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1294197705p2/2610234.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/147962317?book_show_action=true">Feb 13, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Caren" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Caren" href="/user/show/2610234-caren">Caren</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2610234-caren?shelf=adult-nonfiction">adult-nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer147962317" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3715229846332571069">This is a very accessible examination of the recent economic meltdown. You can tell Prof. Reich is a teacher, as the text is very clearly written, so that even an economic dunce like myself can understand his points. I also appreciate that he has given his ideas for concrete measures that address our problems. He is not, in other words, just telling us what went wrong, but is also advising what to do about it. He believes our economy is like a pendulum that swings from eras in which economic ben</span>
  <span id="freeText3715229846332571069" style="display:none">This is a very accessible examination of the recent economic meltdown. You can tell Prof. Reich is a teacher, as the text is very clearly written, so that even an economic dunce like myself can understand his points. I also appreciate that he has given his ideas for concrete measures that address our problems. He is not, in other words, just telling us what went wrong, but is also advising what to do about it. He believes our economy is like a pendulum that swings from eras in which economic benefits are widely shared, to those in which wealth becomes concentrated in a very few hands at the top. Because the middle and lower classes need to spend a greater percentage of their incomes, the economy itself is healthier when income is widely dispersed. He calls the last period when wealth was more evenly dispersed the Great Prosperity, lasting from 1947 to about 1975. He says the pendulum will swing back, but warns that it could be as a result of a close-minded turning inward. He hopes, rather, that it will swing back as a result of genuine reform that widens the 'circle of prosperity' (p. 145). This book is a valuable addition to the economic discussion at hand. Judging by the wait for it at my public library, it is being widely read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3715229846332571069" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


