<div id="review_289148703" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/289148703" />
    <a title="Brenton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7407649-brenton"><img alt="Brenton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1326373275p2/7407649.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/289148703?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brenton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brenton" href="/user/show/7407649-brenton">Brenton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7407649-brenton?shelf=economics-policy">economics-policy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer289148703" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17021688454430939914">This is the third book from Mr. Reich I&apos;ve read, and to initiates I&apos;d definitely recommend this for its brevity (around 150 pages) and ease of reading. His analyses on the financial crisis and the Recession provide ample food for thought to those with an interest in the subject, although he doesn&apos;t cover a lot of new ground in this one. His description of the increasingly pinched middle class and languishing median wage being at the root of the economic crisis is essentially the conclusion I&apos;d a</span>
  <span id="freeText17021688454430939914" style="display:none">This is the third book from Mr. Reich I've read, and to initiates I'd definitely recommend this for its brevity (around 150 pages) and ease of reading. His analyses on the financial crisis and the Recession provide ample food for thought to those with an interest in the subject, although he doesn't cover a lot of new ground in this one. His description of the increasingly pinched middle class and languishing median wage being at the root of the economic crisis is essentially the conclusion I'd already drawn, yet I disagree with most of his remedial prescriptions which he offers at the end of the book. I should note (though most probably know this) that the book comes from a pretty liberal perspective, so a little bias is inevitable, but it's never egregious and the historical facts and statistics should prove valuable to most readers. He was Clinton's secretary of Labor after all. I would consider this the introductory rather than the essential Robert Reich (that distinction goes to Supercapitalism), so give it a go if you have a few hours to spare. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17021688454430939914" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


